Differential Kinematics¶

Differential Kinematics is the study of robot motion using velocities.

Figure 1: The problem of differential kinematics

Why study differential kinematics?

It allows us to study:

  • Non-Holonomic Robots, or robots whose pose is not uniquely defined by a single set of joint angles. The Romi and other mobile robots are non-holonomic because simply specifying their wheel angles does not tell you where they are in the world frame! The entire time history of a non-holonomic robot's motion is required to solve for its pose using integration of velocities.
  • Forces and torques in robot links and joints! This is because differential kinematics is a dual problem to the static analysis of forces and torques, given that the robot's links can be considered idealized power transducers.
  • velocities of a robot's links rather than positions. This can be useful if an inverse kinematic solution for a robot is not readily available, because it can allow us to drive a robot towards a goal location in task space.

In differential kinematics, we will be studying linear and angular velocities. If a robot end effector's velocity is given by:

\begin{equation} \vec{v}_p = \begin{bmatrix}v_x & v_y & v_z \end{bmatrix}^T \end{equation}

And its angular velocity is given by:

\begin{equation} \vec{\omega}_p = \begin{bmatrix}\omega_x & \omega_y & \omega_z \end{bmatrix}^T \end{equation}

We can define a "generalized velocity" for the robot in task space, called a twist, as:

\begin{equation} \vec{\mathcal{V}}_p = \begin{bmatrix}v_x & v_y & v_z & \omega_x & \omega_y & \omega_z \end{bmatrix}^T \end{equation}

Forward Differential Kinematics¶

The problem of forward differential kinematics, or the mapping from a twist in configuration space to a twist in task space, is summarized in Equation 4 below.

\begin{equation} \vec{\mathcal{V}}_p = J(\vec{q})\dot{\vec{q}} \end{equation}

In Equation 4, $J$ is the "Jacobian matrix," $\vec{q}$ is the configuration of the robot, given by the vector of generalized joint positions (angular and/or linear depending on joint types), and $\dot{\vec{q}}$ is the vector of generalized joint velocities for each of the robot's joints. The Jacobian matrix is constructed using partial derivatives, as shown in Equation 5.

\begin{equation} \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}v_x \\ v_y \\ v_z \\ \omega_x \\ \omega_y \\ \omega_z \end{bmatrix}}_{\vec{\mathcal{V}}} = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} \frac{\partial x}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial x}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial x}{\partial q_n} \\ \frac{\partial y}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial y}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial y}{\partial q_n} \\ \frac{\partial z}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial z}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial z}{\partial q_n} \\ \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial q_n} \\ \frac{\partial \theta}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial \theta}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial \theta}{\partial q_n} \\ \frac{\partial \psi}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial \psi}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial \psi}{\partial q_n} \\ \end{bmatrix}}_{J(\vec{q})} \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} \dot{q}_1 \\ \dot{q}_2 \\ \vdots \\ \dot{q}_n \end{bmatrix}}_{\dot{\vec{q}}} \end{equation}

Example: Forward Differential Kinematics for a Two-Link Robot¶

Looking at our forward kinematic equations for the Artybot, we saw:

\begin{equation} ^Ax_P = l_2\cos\theta_2+ l_3\left(\cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3 - \sin\theta_2\sin\theta_3\right) \end{equation} \begin{equation} ^Ay_P = l_2\sin\theta_2 + l_3\left(\sin\theta_2\cos\theta_3 + \cos\theta_2\sin\theta_3\right) \end{equation}

Computing the Jacobian matrix for forward differential kinematics requires taking the following partial derivatives:

\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_2} &= - l_2\sin\theta_2 + l_3\left(-\sin\theta_2\cos\theta_3 - \cos\theta_2\sin\theta_3\right) \\ \frac{\partial ^Ay_p}{\partial \theta_2} &= l_2\cos\theta_2 + l_3\left(\cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3 - \sin\theta_2\sin\theta_3\right) \\ \frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_3} &= -l_3\left(\cos\theta_2\sin\theta_3 + \sin\theta_2\cos\theta_3\right) \\ \frac{\partial ^Ay_p}{\partial \theta_3} &= l_3\left(-\sin\theta_2\sin\theta_3 + \cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3\right) \end{aligned} \end{equation}

Then, the forward differential kinematic equation for the Artybot can be written:

\begin{equation} \begin{bmatrix} ^A\dot{x}_p \\ ^A\dot{y}_p \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_2} & \frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_3} \\ \frac{\partial ^Ay_p}{\partial \theta_2} & \frac{\partial ^Ay_p}{\partial \theta_3} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \dot{\theta}_2 \\ \dot{\theta_3}\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

This equation, by itself, allows us to relate the angular velocities of the Artybot's joints to the allocentric motion of its end effector in task space.

Example: Forward Differential Kinematics for a Two-Link Robot Revisited¶

It's important to remember that differential kinematics is about velocities. This means that a partial derivative from Artybot's Jacobian such as $\frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_2}$ relates the (angular) velocity of link 2 in configuration space to the (linear) velocity of point P in task space. This means that the matrix of Jacobian terms should be (and is) possible to derive using velocity relationships directly, rather than taking partial derivatives of the position equations. We will prove that here. Consider the figure below, which labels velocities directly.

Using rigid body relative velocities, we can write the velocity of point $P$ as follows: \begin{equation} ^A\vec{v}_{P} = ^A\vec{v}_{Oc} + ^A\vec{\omega}_2\times ^A\vec{r}_{OcP} \end{equation}

We know that in the allocentric frame $A$, we can write: \begin{equation} ^A\vec{r}_{OcP} = l_3\left(\cos\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right)\hat{x}_A + \sin\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right)\hat{y}_A\right) \end{equation}

We can also express the angular velocity of link 3 as:

\begin{equation} ^A\vec{\omega}_3 = \left(\dot{\theta_2}+\dot{\theta_3}\right)\hat{z}_A \end{equation}

Substituting Equations 12 and 11 into Equation 10 and computing the relevant cross products gives the following expression for $^A\vec{v}_P$:

\begin{equation} ^A\vec{v}_{P} = ^A\vec{v}_{Oc} + l3\left(\dot{\theta_2}+\dot{\theta_3}\right)\left(\cos\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right)\hat{y}_A-\sin\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right)\hat{x}_A\right) \end{equation}

Then, $^A\vec{v}_{Oc}$ is the only remaining unknown in Equation 13. Using rigid body relative velocities, we can write the velocity of point $O_c$ as follows:

\begin{equation} \require{cancel} ^A\vec{v}_{Oc} = \cancel{^A\vec{v}_{Ob}} + ^A\vec{\omega}_2\times ^A\vec{r}_{ObOc} \end{equation}

Noting that $^A\vec{\omega}_2=\dot{\theta_2}\hat{z}_A$, and that $^A\vec{r}_{ObOc}=l_2\left(\cos\theta_2\hat{x}_A+\sin\theta_2\hat{y}_A\right)$,

\begin{equation} ^A\vec{v}_{Oc} = l_2\dot{\theta_2}\left(\cos\theta_2\hat{y}_A-\sin\theta_2\hat{x}_A\right) \end{equation}

Substituting Equation 15 into Equation 13 yields a complete description of $^A\vec{v}_P$ as a function of the robot's configuration and its configuration velocity:

\begin{equation} ^A\vec{v}_P = l_2\dot{\theta_2}\left(\cos\theta_2\hat{y}_A-\sin\theta_2\hat{x}_A\right) + l_3\left(\dot{\theta_2}+\dot{\theta_3}\right)\left(\cos\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right)\hat{y}_A-\sin\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right)\hat{x}_A\right) \end{equation}

Writing Equation 16 as a vector-matrix equation for $^A\vec{v}_P = \begin{bmatrix}^A\dot{x}_P & ^A\dot{y}_P\end{bmatrix}^T$ yields:

\begin{equation} \begin{bmatrix} ^A\dot{x}_p \\ ^A\dot{y}_p \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\left(l_2\sin\theta_2+l_3\sin\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right)\right)\ & -l_3\sin\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right) \\ l_2\cos\theta_2 +l_3\cos\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right) & l_3\cos\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right) \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \dot{\theta}_2 \\ \dot{\theta_3}\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

If this equation is consistent with our definition of the Jacobian and its role in differential kinematics, Equation 17 should be equivalent to Equation 9 with Equation 8 substituted in! In other words, the following terms should be equivalent:

\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_2} &=& - l_2\sin\theta_2 + l_3\left(-\sin\theta_2\cos\theta_3 - \cos\theta_2\sin\theta_3\right) &=& -\left(l_2\sin\theta_2+l_3\sin\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right)\right) \\ \frac{\partial ^Ay_p}{\partial \theta_2} &=& l_2\cos\theta_2 + l_3\left(\cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3 - \sin\theta_2\sin\theta_3\right) &=& l_2\cos\theta_2 +l_3\cos\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right) \\ \frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_3} &=& -l_3\left(\cos\theta_2\sin\theta_3 + \sin\theta_2\cos\theta_3\right) &=& -l_3\sin\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right) \\ \frac{\partial ^Ay_p}{\partial \theta_3} &=& l_3\left(-\sin\theta_2\sin\theta_3 + \cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3\right) &=& l_3\cos\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right) \end{aligned} \end{equation}

Using the angle addition identities: \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \sin\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right) &= \sin\theta_2\cos\theta_3 +\cos\theta_2\sin\theta_3 \\ \cos\left(\theta_2+\theta_3\right) &= \cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3 -\sin\theta_2\sin\theta_3 \end{aligned} \end{equation} We can see that they are! This confirms that the Jacobian can be obtained from a positional kinematic solution, but also from a direct analysis of the velocities of a robot's links.

Example: Romi Forward Differential Kinematics¶

We have actually done differential kinematics for the Romi before when we studied Odometry!! As a reminder, The problem setup looked something like this:

What we found was that:

\begin{equation} \dot{\psi} = \frac{v_R-v_L}{2r} \end{equation}

and

\begin{equation} v_b = \frac{v_L+v_R}{2} \end{equation}

As it turns out, this already was a statement of forward differential kinematics (in body-fixed coordinates, rather than task space or allocentric coordinates). Noting that if the radius of the Romi's wheels is $R_w$, $v_R = \omega_R R_w$ and $v_L = \omega_L R_w$, and considering the Romi's configuration space as $\begin{bmatrix} \omega_R & \omega_L\end{bmatrix}^T$, we can write:

\begin{equation} \begin{bmatrix}^B\dot{x} \\ ^B\dot{y} \\ ^B\dot{\psi} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{R_w}{2} & -\frac{R_w}{2} \\ 0 & 0 \\\frac{R_w}{2r} & -\frac{R_w}{2r} \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} \omega_R \\ \omega_L\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

The body-fixed velocity vector $^B\vec{v}$ can easily be transformed into allocentric coordinates using the rotation matrix $_B^AR(\psi) = \begin{bmatrix}\cos\psi& -\sin\psi \\ \sin\psi& \cos\psi \end{bmatrix}$, which alllows us to write the forward kinematic equation for task space directly:

\begin{equation} \begin{bmatrix}^A\dot{x} \\ ^A\dot{y} \\ ^A\dot{\psi} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{R_w\cos\psi}{2} & -\frac{R_w\cos \psi}{2} \\ \frac{R_w\sin\psi}{2} & -\frac{R_w\sin \psi}{2}\\\frac{R_w}{2r} & -\frac{R_w}{2r} \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} \omega_R \\ \omega_L\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

Note that in Equation 12, there is no explicit dependence of J on wheel angles $\theta_L,\theta_R$, but in Equation 13, there is dependence on $\psi$, which is not directly related to either $\theta_L$ or $\theta_R$. This is a statement of the robot's non-holonomic nature-- to know $\psi$, we need the entire time history of $\theta_L$ and $\theta_R$! We cannot simply map $\psi$ to those wheel angles directly, like we could with ArtyBot.

Inverse Differential Kinematics¶

Inverse differential kinematics involves calculating the joint speeds (in configuration space) necessary to achieve a particular end-effector velocity in task space. In theory, this means we can make our robot move towards (and eventually reach) a goal in task space without computing a position-based inverse kinematic solution. This approach does not always work, but when it does, it is often easier!

If the robot's Jacobian is invertible, the inverse differential kinematic equation, which maps generalized velocities in task space to generalized joint velocities, is given by:

\begin{equation} \dot{\vec{q}} = J(\vec{q})^{-1}\vec{\mathcal{V}} \end{equation}

For J to be invertible, its determinant cannot be zero, and it must be square. Often, however, J is not square, because the dimensionality of the task and configuration spaces for the robot are not the same. In those cases, we can use the pseudoinverse of J:

\begin{equation} J^+ = J^T\left(JJ^T\right)^{-1} \end{equation}

Using inverse differential kinematics to reach a goal in task space¶

One of the key applications of inverse differential kinematics is to sidestep the need for a full IK solution. By using the error between where the robot should go in task space and where the robot actually is in task space, we can use inverse differential kinematics to drive the robot's end effector towards our goal. This is a form of feedback control (which we will cover explicitly later).

If the subscript "d" indicates a static "goal" value, and we define "eror" for the robot's end effector in task space as:

\begin{equation} \vec{e} = \begin{bmatrix} x_d-x & y_d - y& \cdots & \omega_{nd} - \omega_n \end{bmatrix}^T \end{equation}

Then we can progressively drive a robot's end effector towards the goal using the pseudoinverse of its Jacobian matrix:

\begin{equation} \vec{q} = J^+ e \end{equation}

As error gets smaller, the robot will move more and more slowly and (hopefully) approach the goal.

Using Differential Kinematics to compute static robot joint forces and torques¶

One of the most powerful ways to use differential kinematics is for an analysis of the static forces and moments in a robot in configuration space, given an externally applied force and/or moment in task space. We might ask, for example, what motor torques $\mu_2$ and $\mu_3$ are required on the ArtyBot if someone pushes on its pen $P$ with a force $\vec{F}_{P,applied}$.

Note that $\mu$ will be used to denote Torque rather than $T$ to avoid confusion with our homogeneous transformations $T$.

A quick summary of "Statics"¶

As a review(?) of Statics (ES226 if you took it at Lafayette), in a static force and moment analysis we assume that a rigid body or system of rigid bodies (truss, rigid body, whatever) is not accelerating. This means that we can write two key vector equations:

\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \sum\vec{F} &= \vec{0} \\ \sum\vec{\mu} &= \vec{0} \end{aligned} \end{equation}

where $\vec{F}$ is the vector (in 2D or 3D space) of forces applied to a system and $\vec{\mu}$ is the vector of torques (moments) applied to the system. Note that these two equations apply regardless of where we draw our system boundary. In ES226 (Statics), students learn to "section" members in a complex truss system (which is much like a multi-link robot) and apply these two equations at the component and/or system-level as appropriate to create a system of equations with an equivalent number of equations and unknowns using analyses at different system scales.

Using differential kinematics to solve statics problems¶

When using differential kinematics to solve statics problems, it's helpful to introduce a "generalized force," in much the same way that we introduced a "generalized velocity" in the derivation of differential kinematics. If we define $\begin{bmatrix} F_x & F_y & F_z \end{bmatrix}^T$ as the force vector $\vec{F}$ and $\begin{bmatrix} \mu_x & \mu_y & \mu_z \end{bmatrix}^T$ as the Torque (moment) vector $\vec{\mu}$, we can define a "generalized force" called a "Wrench" as:

\begin{equation} \vec{\tau} = \begin{bmatrix} F_x & F_y & F_z & \mu_x & \mu_y & \mu_z \end{bmatrix}^T \end{equation}

For a robot with $N$ links and $N-1$ joints connecting them (in an open kinematic chain), we can say that a Wrench $\tau_i$ exists for each of the $N-1$ joints that represents how much force and torque must be reacted by that joint. The wrench will be partially reacted by the structure of the joint (reaction forces at the 'pin' of a hinge joint, for example) and partially reacted by the motor that actuates the joint.

For example, on the ArtyBot, both of the planar joints actuating $\theta_2,\theta_3$ are revolutes about the $\hat{z}$ direction, so the torque reacted by joint 2 would be the $\mu_z$ portion of $\vec{\tau}_2$.

Looking at the general case for a robot with a Wrench applied to its end effector, let's call that wrench $\vec{\tau}_{P,e}$. This is the wrench that the environment is applying to the robot. Static equivalency (see section 4.1) insists that by Newton's 3rd Law: \begin{equation} \vec{\tau}_{P,e}=-\vec{\tau}_{P} \end{equation}

where $\vec{\tau}_{P}$ is the wrench the robot applies to the environment.

In ES103, you learned that for an idealized transducer,

\begin{equation} \dot{W}_{in}=\dot{W}_{out} \end{equation}

For a rotational to mechanical transducer, for example, you could write (in vector form):

\begin{equation} \vec{\mu}\cdot\vec{\Omega} = \vec{F}\cdot\vec{v} \end{equation}

in a more general sense, we could say that a robot is a little bit like a "transducer" from the configuration space to the task space. In other words, the power $\dot{W}_{conf}$ the robot supplies in the configuration space must be equal to the power $\dot{W}_{task}$ that the robot generates in the task space.

We can express the total power (as a sum of both translational and rotational) supplied by the robot in configuration space as a dot product between the wrench representing the "generalized forces" applied by a robot's actuators (we'll call it $\tau_c$) and the twist representing the robot's joints' generalized velocities: \begin{equation} \dot{W}_{conf} = \vec{\tau}_c^T\dot{q} = \begin{bmatrix}\tau_1 & \tau_2 & \cdots & \tau_{N-1} \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\dot{q}_1 \\ \dot{q}_2 \\ \vdots \\ \dot{q}_{N-1}\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

We can similarly express the total power (as a sum of both translational and rotational) applied by the robot on its environment at point $P$ in task space as another dot product: \begin{equation} \dot{W}_{task} = \vec{\tau}_{P}^T\vec{\mathcal{V}} = \begin{bmatrix}F_x & F_y & F_z & \mu_x & \mu_y & \mu_z \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}v_x \\ v_y \\ v_z \\ \omega_x \\ \omega_y \\ \omega_z\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

And we know that if there are no losses in the robot, if it acts as an "idealized transducer," then: \begin{equation} \dot{W}_{conf} = \dot{W}_{task} \end{equation}

Luckily, we know from differential kinematics that: \begin{equation} \vec{\mathcal{V}} = J(\vec{q})\dot{\vec{q}} \end{equation}

which means that we can write our first law equivalence of input and output power as:

\begin{equation} \vec{\tau}_c^T\dot{\vec{q}} = \vec{\tau}_{P}^T\vec{\mathcal{V}} = \vec{\tau}_{P}^TJ(\vec{q})\dot{\vec{q}} \end{equation}

Canceling the common power of $\dot{\vec{q}}$ (a very common move in ES103!) yields:

\begin{equation} \vec{\tau}_c^T = \vec{\tau}_{P}^TJ(\vec{q}) \end{equation}

Which implies:

\begin{equation} \vec{\tau}_c = J(\vec{q})^T\vec{\tau}_{P} \end{equation}

Where, as a reminder, $\vec{\tau}_c$ is the vector of generalized joint forces applied by the robot in configuration space while $\vec{\tau}_{P}$ is the vector of applied generalized end-effector forces in task space. If the wrench applied by the environment on the robot in task space $\tau_{P,e}$ is known, it is easy to compute $\tau_{P}=-\tau_{P,e}$ by Newton's third law for static equilibrium.

Summary¶

The robot's Jacobian can be used to map a "wrench" applied by the robot's joints in configuration space to the "wrench" applied by the robot in task space. Namely:

\begin{equation} \vec{\tau}_c = J^T\vec{\tau}_P = \begin{bmatrix}\frac{\partial x}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial y}{\partial q_1} & \cdots & \frac{\partial \theta_z}{\partial q_1} \\ \frac{\partial x}{\partial q_2} & \frac{\partial y}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial \theta_z}{\partial q_2} \\ \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & \cdots \\ \frac{\partial x}{\partial q_n} & \frac{\partial y}{\partial q_n} & \cdots & \frac{\partial \theta_z}{\partial q_n} \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}F_x \\ F_y \\ F_z \\ \vdots \\ \mu_z\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

The same approach can be used to invert the process using the pseudoinverse of the Jacobian's transpose. In other words,

\begin{equation} \vec{\tau}_P = \left(J^T\right)^+\vec{\tau}_c \end{equation}

NOTES

  • When a "singularity" occurs in the Jacobian and it is not invertible, this affects both the static force/moment analysis as well as the velocity analysis, but in different ways.
  • Be careul about what coordinate system you use when deriving "J" and defining the "task space." Know which coordinate system you're expressing $\vec{\tau}_{P}$ in!
